snippet.textDisplay: Though I'm not a fan, I understand the appeal of cats as a broadway musical, where it's about coming to see the skill of the dancers and be transported live into the weird world created by the sets costumes and lighting.  Also the catchy song cycles.  It's like Dr. Seuss vignettes and doesn't need to have a story that makes sense.  But...all of that works against it when it's being adapted to a film though.  What's a fun megamusical experience live for people who enjoy that sort of thing is a boring mess as a film.  (Made worse with bad CGI)

snippet.textDisplay: Cats on stage was a musical dance review. It had no plot. It was a book of poems set to music by Andrew Lloyd Weber by T.S. Elliott. What did anyone expect in a movie? You’ve made this a joke. The movie came out badly. Amongst how many other bad movies that studios have put out. I’m not defending it but Cats was always going to be divisive. It’s not a horror show. It’s not Dante’s 10th level of hell. It just had many faults but was not the crime of the century.
